00:06:02.060 --> 00:06:03.950
and thanks also for
giving me the opportunity

00:06:03.950 --> 00:06:05.290
to return to Berkeley,

00:06:05.290 --> 00:06:08.660
which is the place of
my intellectual roots.

00:06:08.660 --> 00:06:11.463
Much of what I do is
really sort of flowed from

00:06:11.463 --> 00:06:14.290
the concepts, ideas, and approaches

00:06:14.290 --> 00:06:17.650
that I learned during my
time here at Berkeley.

00:06:17.650 --> 00:06:20.100
So today we're gonna talk about
the great transformations.

00:06:20.100 --> 00:06:23.090
And if you take the four
and a half billion year

00:06:23.090 --> 00:06:23.961
history of our planet,

00:06:23.961 --> 00:06:26.540
you can begin to visualize

00:06:26.540 --> 00:06:28.440
in a number of different ways.

00:06:28.440 --> 00:06:30.410
And one of the most
common ways to visualize

00:06:30.410 --> 00:06:31.730
the history of our planet,

00:06:31.730 --> 00:06:35.050
is as some sort of
linear series of events.

00:06:35.050 --> 00:06:37.350
And so this is one taken from a textbook.

00:06:37.350 --> 00:06:39.391
It's from Press and Siever,

00:06:39.391 --> 00:06:42.190
a very prominent geology textbook.

00:06:42.190 --> 00:06:45.410
And what you see is this
linear series is depicted

00:06:45.410 --> 00:06:48.880
as sort of a corkscrew so
they can fit it on the page.

00:06:48.880 --> 00:06:52.650
And you see the various
events and the trajectory

00:06:52.650 --> 00:06:54.250
in the history of our planet,

00:06:54.250 --> 00:06:56.390
and the history of life on our planet

00:06:56.390 --> 00:06:58.773
from the presence of the first rocks,

00:06:58.773 --> 00:07:01.730
the earliest visible life
in the fossil record,

00:07:01.730 --> 00:07:05.540
the origin of bodies
and plants and animals,

00:07:05.540 --> 00:07:07.260
and then you see sort of the major events

00:07:07.260 --> 00:07:09.500
in the history of vertebrate life,

00:07:09.500 --> 00:07:11.230
creatures with bones,

00:07:11.230 --> 00:07:13.650
the shift from water to land,

00:07:13.650 --> 00:07:16.370
the shift to the origin
of dinosaurs and so forth.

00:07:16.370 --> 00:07:18.240
When you look at the world this way,

00:07:18.240 --> 00:07:19.740
in this sort of linear way,

00:07:19.740 --> 00:07:21.810
from beginning to present,

00:07:21.810 --> 00:07:23.190
what you sort of see is there are times

00:07:23.190 --> 00:07:24.960
that kind of look revolutionary

00:07:24.960 --> 00:07:26.880
or the sort of revolution in the air

00:07:26.880 --> 00:07:28.770
where there are big things happening.

00:07:28.770 --> 00:07:32.800
And those time periods have
always attracted my attention

00:07:32.800 --> 00:07:34.170
for one reason or another.

00:07:34.170 --> 00:07:36.540
And that's why I've ended up focusing

00:07:36.540 --> 00:07:38.870
on two time periods in
the history of life,

00:07:38.870 --> 00:07:41.100
the Triassic and the Devonian,

00:07:41.100 --> 00:07:42.940
time periods from 200 million years ago

00:07:42.940 --> 00:07:46.130
and about 375 million years ago.

00:07:46.130 --> 00:07:47.790
But anyway, I'm gonna show you

00:07:47.790 --> 00:07:50.240
how this kind of way of
depicting the history

00:07:50.240 --> 00:07:52.150
and the sequence of events in our world,

00:07:52.150 --> 00:07:54.410
actually it gets in the way

00:07:54.410 --> 00:07:56.840
of really understanding and decomposing

00:07:56.840 --> 00:07:59.790
some of the main events we see
in the history of our planet

00:07:59.790 --> 00:08:01.580
and life on our planet.

00:08:01.580 --> 00:08:02.872
And what I'm gonna do is

00:08:02.872 --> 00:08:04.640
I'm gonna take one particular example,

00:08:04.640 --> 00:08:06.400
one major transformation,

00:08:06.400 --> 00:08:09.150
the shift from fish that lives in water

00:08:09.150 --> 00:08:11.530
to limbed animals that live on land.

00:08:11.530 --> 00:08:14.950
I'm gonna take that shift and
really analyze it in detail

00:08:14.950 --> 00:08:17.040
to show you how an integrative approach,

00:08:17.040 --> 00:08:20.020
integrating fossils, and
studies with living organisms,

00:08:20.020 --> 00:08:23.370
can tell us a lot about how
this transformation happened.

00:08:23.370 --> 00:08:24.930
And I'm gonna use that as a microcosm,

00:08:24.930 --> 00:08:28.110
an example really of how we can approach

00:08:28.110 --> 00:08:31.060
all the other transformations
that are out there.

00:08:31.060 --> 00:08:34.430
So let's start with the
transformation from water to land.

00:08:34.430 --> 00:08:37.660
So here what we have the
transformation from water to land.

00:08:37.660 --> 00:08:40.620
And you see here, I've shown a cartoon.

00:08:40.620 --> 00:08:43.080
This is a complete
caricature of the situation.

00:08:43.080 --> 00:08:44.790
And if you were to sort
of blue sky this thing,

00:08:44.790 --> 00:08:46.430
on the back of an envelope,

00:08:46.430 --> 00:08:47.610
and you know look at a fish,

00:08:47.610 --> 00:08:51.310
and look at a land living
vertebrate animal with bones,

00:08:51.310 --> 00:08:53.700
you can sort of say wow
geesh, life in water

00:08:53.700 --> 00:08:55.800
is vastly different from life on land.

00:08:55.800 --> 00:08:57.710
Almost every single
system of these creatures

00:08:57.710 --> 00:08:58.790
had to change.

00:08:58.790 --> 00:09:01.430
And I just showed you
several here, I mean,

00:09:01.430 --> 00:09:04.510
respiration, feeding,
locomotion, and head mobility.

00:09:04.510 --> 00:09:06.230
And if you look at the end
states of this transition

00:09:06.230 --> 00:09:09.180
it looks really large and
indeed almost impossible.

00:09:09.180 --> 00:09:11.250
Now just take a few of
them, take respiration,

00:09:11.250 --> 00:09:13.430
and you have a shift from creatures

00:09:13.430 --> 00:09:14.900
that are largely water breathing

00:09:14.900 --> 00:09:16.490
to creatures that are air breathing.

00:09:16.490 --> 00:09:18.927
This involves whole sweeps
of changes to organs

00:09:18.927 --> 00:09:21.074
and the ways that organs develop,

00:09:21.074 --> 00:09:24.990
and circulatory systems,
and lungs and so forth.

00:09:24.990 --> 00:09:26.960
Feeding, feeding in water

00:09:26.960 --> 00:09:28.680
is very different from feeding in land.

00:09:28.680 --> 00:09:30.270
You go from where you have water

00:09:30.270 --> 00:09:33.410
where you can suck the food into the mouth

00:09:33.410 --> 00:09:35.900
by changing the volume of the mouth cavity

00:09:35.900 --> 00:09:38.360
to biting, where on land you can't suck in

00:09:38.360 --> 00:09:42.700
unless you're a Hoover
Dustette or a vacuum cleaner.

00:09:42.700 --> 00:09:44.910
It's really more of a biting approach

00:09:44.910 --> 00:09:48.610
to the capturing and chewing food.

00:09:48.610 --> 00:09:51.170
Locomotion is completely
different on land from water.

00:09:51.170 --> 00:09:52.520
I mean, here you have water supported,

00:09:52.520 --> 00:09:54.790
where you basically have to
support yourself in gravity,

00:09:54.790 --> 00:09:55.900
it's not gravity supported,

00:09:55.900 --> 00:09:58.830
but it's basically you're
dealing with gravity as a force.

00:09:58.830 --> 00:10:00.660
And the skeleton had to change

00:10:00.660 --> 00:10:03.440
from a water supported to
actually dealing with gravity

00:10:03.440 --> 00:10:06.633
as a force, on the
ground, on the substrate.

00:10:07.480 --> 00:10:09.250
And there's all kinds of other
changes associated with this.

00:10:09.250 --> 00:10:11.110
Head mobility, you know fish have heads

00:10:11.110 --> 00:10:13.650
that are largely connected to the body

00:10:16.581 --> 00:10:18.610
by a series of bones so
when you move the head

00:10:18.610 --> 00:10:20.470
you move the rest of the body.

00:10:20.470 --> 00:10:21.900
They don't have necks whereas

00:10:21.900 --> 00:10:22.733
land living creatures have necks,

00:10:22.733 --> 00:10:24.950
their head can move
independently to the body.

00:10:24.950 --> 00:10:26.520
Now for this whole talk
I could have gone through

00:10:26.520 --> 00:10:27.560
a whole long list of things

00:10:27.560 --> 00:10:28.890
from excretion, reproduction,

00:10:28.890 --> 00:10:30.530
and all kinds of different systems

00:10:30.530 --> 00:10:31.800
that would have to change.

00:10:31.800 --> 00:10:34.020
And when you look at these
systems, you'd say golly gee,

00:10:34.020 --> 00:10:37.560
I don't see how this
transformation could ever happen.

00:10:37.560 --> 00:10:40.850
So my sort of goal for the last 20 years

00:10:40.850 --> 00:10:43.220
has really been to look at this in detail.

00:10:43.220 --> 00:10:44.510
To try to collect new fossils,

00:10:44.510 --> 00:10:46.310
to try to collect understandings from

00:10:46.310 --> 00:10:48.100
living recent creatures

00:10:48.100 --> 00:10:52.120
that tell us a lot about how fish achieve

00:10:52.120 --> 00:10:53.820
this important shift in evolution.

00:10:54.720 --> 00:10:56.930
This was sort of the
state of affairs in 1987.

00:10:56.930 --> 00:11:00.220
This is a textbook written
by one of my predecessors

00:11:00.220 --> 00:11:02.600
at the University of
Chicago, Len Rodinsky.

00:11:02.600 --> 00:11:06.450
And I saw this in 1987
in a graduate seminar

00:11:06.450 --> 00:11:08.100
and it really attracted my interest.

00:11:08.100 --> 00:11:09.980
'Cause what he showed is a
lobe-finned fish on the top.

00:11:09.980 --> 00:11:11.360
This is a creature from about,

00:11:11.360 --> 00:11:13.220
the first ones of these appeared

00:11:13.220 --> 00:11:15.120
about 380 million years ago.

00:11:15.120 --> 00:11:18.800
And on the bottom you see
an early limbed creature.

00:11:18.800 --> 00:11:20.450
This is a creature from Greenland,

00:11:20.450 --> 00:11:22.850
at least that's what we thought
it looked like at the time,

00:11:22.850 --> 00:11:26.140
from about 365-ish or
so million years ago.

00:11:26.140 --> 00:11:27.297
And I remember looking at this and saying,

00:11:27.297 --> 00:11:29.307
"Golly gee, this is a big transition.

00:11:29.307 --> 00:11:31.600
"There's a lot for features
that have to change."

00:11:31.600 --> 00:11:34.500
And to approach this,
it became pretty clear

00:11:34.500 --> 00:11:35.333
that if we wanted to address this,

00:11:35.333 --> 00:11:37.320
we had to find new fossils.

00:11:37.320 --> 00:11:39.150
In fact if we wanted to find new fossils

00:11:39.150 --> 00:11:40.500
that bridge this gap,

00:11:40.500 --> 00:11:43.460
we had to find whole new
places to look for fossils.

00:11:43.460 --> 00:11:46.040
So off we went to start looking for places

00:11:46.040 --> 00:11:48.024
to find new fossils to tell us about

00:11:48.024 --> 00:11:50.063
this important anatomical shift.

00:11:50.910 --> 00:11:52.750
And so like paleontologists everywhere,

00:11:52.750 --> 00:11:55.170
there are actually some simple rules to go

00:11:55.170 --> 00:11:56.940
when you want to design a new expedition

00:11:56.940 --> 00:11:59.490
to look for fossils.

00:11:59.490 --> 00:12:01.520
We look for places in the
world that have sort of a

00:12:01.520 --> 00:12:03.550
convergence of three things.

00:12:03.550 --> 00:12:05.440
The first is you look
for places in the world

00:12:05.440 --> 00:12:07.110
that have rocks of the right age

00:12:07.110 --> 00:12:09.330
to answer the question
that you're interested in.

00:12:09.330 --> 00:12:11.501
I mean so I'm interested in
the shift from water to land

00:12:11.501 --> 00:12:15.290
and fish, so it's no mystery
that I'm interested in rocks

00:12:15.290 --> 00:12:20.290
around 380 to 365 or so million years old.

00:12:20.490 --> 00:12:22.850
The next thing is you look
for rocks of the right type.

00:12:22.850 --> 00:12:26.680
Not every kind of rock preserves fossils.

00:12:26.680 --> 00:12:28.410
Sedimentary rocks preserve fossils

00:12:28.410 --> 00:12:30.650
better volcanic or metamorphic ones.

00:12:30.650 --> 00:12:32.390
And indeed within the sedimentary rocks

00:12:32.390 --> 00:12:35.100
there are certain
depositional environments,

00:12:35.100 --> 00:12:37.130
environments where those rocks were formed

00:12:37.130 --> 00:12:40.180
which are more likely
to preserve fossil bone

00:12:40.180 --> 00:12:42.550
than others for a variety of reason.

00:12:42.550 --> 00:12:46.250
One because they might reflect
areas where creatures lived.

00:12:46.250 --> 00:12:48.470
The other is, because they were formed

00:12:48.470 --> 00:12:52.930
in very gentle environments
with little erosion

00:12:52.930 --> 00:12:54.300
so that whatever fossils were there

00:12:54.300 --> 00:12:56.283
were preserved in some detail.

00:12:57.200 --> 00:12:58.664
The third variable is really important.

00:12:58.664 --> 00:12:59.850
Actually it's one of
the most important ones.

00:12:59.850 --> 00:13:01.954
It does me no good if my wonderful rocks

00:13:01.954 --> 00:13:04.420
of the right age and the right type

00:13:04.420 --> 00:13:06.390
are buried five miles underground.

00:13:06.390 --> 00:13:08.850
I mean these rocks have to
be exposed to the surface.

00:13:08.850 --> 00:13:10.210
I mean what we do as paleontologists

00:13:10.210 --> 00:13:12.393
is walk over rocks for long days,

00:13:13.331 --> 00:13:15.490
just to find bones weathering out.

00:13:15.490 --> 00:13:17.550
So it's really exposures,
rocks of the right age,

00:13:17.550 --> 00:13:18.950
and rocks of the right type.

00:13:18.950 --> 00:13:21.540
There's a third variable when
I stated out on this quest.

00:13:21.540 --> 00:13:23.350
And that was lack of money.

00:13:23.350 --> 00:13:26.360
And so I started on my,
this is really true.

00:13:26.360 --> 00:13:28.780
I started my first academic job

00:13:28.780 --> 00:13:30.880
after leaving Berkeley as a Miller Fellow,

00:13:30.880 --> 00:13:34.589
I moved to Philadelphia as
a young assistant professor

00:13:34.589 --> 00:13:37.160
here in the southeastern
portion of the state.

00:13:37.160 --> 00:13:40.261
And what I wanted really
was a field program

00:13:40.261 --> 00:13:44.010
that I could do on the cheap,
or on weekends out of my car.

00:13:44.010 --> 00:13:47.030
You know paying like
turnpike tolls and gas money.

00:13:47.030 --> 00:13:48.930
And the first thing I did was obviously

00:13:48.930 --> 00:13:52.150
pulled out a geological map
of New York and Pennsylvania

00:13:52.150 --> 00:13:53.610
and the first thing you
see when you pull out

00:13:53.610 --> 00:13:56.020
a geological map of New
York and Pennsylvania

00:13:56.020 --> 00:13:58.550
is you see that the place is just littered

00:13:58.550 --> 00:14:00.470
with Devonian Age rocks.

00:14:00.470 --> 00:14:02.015
So I basically stripped out everything

00:14:02.015 --> 00:14:04.860
unimportant out of the
state of Pennsylvania

00:14:04.860 --> 00:14:08.240
and what's left here is
the Devonian. (laughs)

00:14:08.240 --> 00:14:10.949
And you can see, I mean it's
loaded with Devonian Age rocks.

00:14:10.949 --> 00:14:14.920
And these span an age pretty
much in the late Devonian

00:14:14.920 --> 00:14:16.540
is the ones I was interested in.

00:14:16.540 --> 00:14:19.440
And these are rocks about
365 million years old

00:14:19.440 --> 00:14:21.730
from the Catskill
Formation and they extend

00:14:21.730 --> 00:14:24.620
into New York and into the
Catskills, hence the name.

00:14:24.620 --> 00:14:25.660
So it's pretty clear,

00:14:25.660 --> 00:14:29.470
from about a three hour
drive from Philadelphia,

00:14:29.470 --> 00:14:33.376
you know I had access
to Devonian Age rocks.

00:14:33.376 --> 00:14:35.290
Got even better when we started to look

00:14:35.290 --> 00:14:38.810
at the geology of these rocks
and what geologists knew.

00:14:38.810 --> 00:14:41.250
The Pennsylvania State Geological Survey

00:14:41.250 --> 00:14:42.870
was mapping these rocks for years

00:14:42.870 --> 00:14:45.950
and concocted a cartoon really version

00:14:45.950 --> 00:14:48.380
of what Pennsylvania
was like at this time.

00:14:48.380 --> 00:14:49.760
If you wanna think what
Pennsylvania was like

00:14:49.760 --> 00:14:52.290
in the Devonian, get
Pittsburgh, Harrisburg,

00:14:52.290 --> 00:14:56.610
and Philadelphia out of your
brain and think Amazon Delta.

00:14:56.610 --> 00:14:59.870
This is really just a cartoon
of the reconstruction.

00:14:59.870 --> 00:15:01.880
Essentially a series of highlands

00:15:01.880 --> 00:15:04.550
to the eastern part of
the state of Pennsylvania,

00:15:04.550 --> 00:15:07.350
and an inland sea to the
west, called the Catskill Sea.

00:15:07.350 --> 00:15:08.480
So if you look at the Devonian rocks

00:15:08.480 --> 00:15:10.010
of Pittsburgh or Cleveland,

00:15:10.010 --> 00:15:13.940
you'll find they're marine
rocks from this inland sea.

00:15:13.940 --> 00:15:17.873
And a series a rivers that
drain from east to west.

00:15:18.830 --> 00:15:20.420
Now if you're a paleontologist

00:15:20.420 --> 00:15:22.460
interested in the transition

00:15:22.460 --> 00:15:24.670
from fish to limbed animal,

00:15:24.670 --> 00:15:26.620
and you wanna find
fossils along those lines,

00:15:26.620 --> 00:15:27.750
this is perfect.

00:15:27.750 --> 00:15:30.230
Because you can sample if you're lucky,

00:15:30.230 --> 00:15:33.300
ancient seas, ancient estuaries,

00:15:33.300 --> 00:15:36.460
all the way up the stream if you're lucky.

00:15:36.460 --> 00:15:38.530
I was also lucky in this regard

00:15:38.530 --> 00:15:41.490
because a graduate student
started working with me.

00:15:41.490 --> 00:15:42.323
This is Ted Daeschler here,

00:15:42.323 --> 00:15:43.410
this is a picture of us last year,

00:15:43.410 --> 00:15:44.480
not when he was a graduate student.

00:15:44.480 --> 00:15:46.464
We were a lot younger when
this whole thing started.

00:15:46.464 --> 00:15:48.900
But Ted and I have been working ever since

00:15:48.900 --> 00:15:52.430
and Ted really has been a
major, major, major part

00:15:52.430 --> 00:15:55.890
of much of the work, fossil
work, you're gonna hear about.

00:15:55.890 --> 00:15:57.180
But Pennsylvania has a problem,

00:15:57.180 --> 00:15:58.300
I mean it has two of these variables,

00:15:58.300 --> 00:16:00.570
it has rocks the right age
and rocks of the right type,

00:16:00.570 --> 00:16:03.180
but unfortunately it's not
renowned for its exposures.

00:16:03.180 --> 00:16:04.600
Pennsylvania's not a desert.

00:16:04.600 --> 00:16:07.330
And so it turns out the
best exposures for us

00:16:07.330 --> 00:16:08.950
were areas where the Pennsylvania

00:16:08.950 --> 00:16:12.710
Department Of Transportation
decided to put in new roads.

00:16:12.710 --> 00:16:14.860
What would happen, or
where there are streams,

00:16:14.860 --> 00:16:16.200
but it's actually the road cuts that were

00:16:16.200 --> 00:16:17.590
kind of a critical thing.

00:16:17.590 --> 00:16:19.820
What happens is, you know
Penn DOT will come through

00:16:19.820 --> 00:16:21.220
and you know when they want to put a road

00:16:21.220 --> 00:16:23.000
or a bend in a road or widen a road,

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:26.220
what would they do, they'd
blow it up, they blow up rock.

00:16:26.220 --> 00:16:28.100
When they blow up rock,
if we were really lucky,

00:16:28.100 --> 00:16:29.950
they'd blow up rock in the Devonian.

00:16:29.950 --> 00:16:31.390
And if you're super really lucky,

00:16:31.390 --> 00:16:34.590
they'd blow up rock in
you know the right part

00:16:34.590 --> 00:16:37.810
of the delta system of the Devonian rocks.

00:16:37.810 --> 00:16:41.335
And to his was one area
which was widened in the 70s.

00:16:41.335 --> 00:16:43.210
It's a road about an hour north

00:16:43.210 --> 00:16:45.060
of State College, Pennsylvania.

00:16:45.060 --> 00:16:47.670
It's a road cut called,
don't be surprised,

00:16:47.670 --> 00:16:49.730
Red Hill, 'cause it's a red hill.

00:16:49.730 --> 00:16:53.503
A large road cut and when
it was widened in the 70s,

00:16:53.503 --> 00:16:56.340
it exposed a series of
the strata, the beds here

00:16:56.340 --> 00:16:58.250
which you can see going up.

00:16:58.250 --> 00:17:00.720
This is really a fluvial
river environment.

00:17:00.720 --> 00:17:02.690
And what you see as you walk through here

00:17:02.690 --> 00:17:05.440
are cross-sections of ancient streams.

00:17:05.440 --> 00:17:08.850
Ancient streams, their
overbank or marginal deposits,

00:17:08.850 --> 00:17:10.560
sometimes you'll see point bars,

00:17:10.560 --> 00:17:12.430
these streams look like they meander,

00:17:12.430 --> 00:17:15.836
it has a very classic sort
of deltaic even part of,

00:17:15.836 --> 00:17:18.950
and some meandering
streams within this area.

00:17:18.950 --> 00:17:20.740
So it's a really rich area.

00:17:20.740 --> 00:17:22.120
And you see the scale here.

00:17:22.120 --> 00:17:23.890
There's a car and there's
a human being for scale.

00:17:23.890 --> 00:17:25.400
What is actually our research program was,

00:17:25.400 --> 00:17:27.480
was to climb up and down
the sides of these hills.

00:17:27.480 --> 00:17:29.880
It got a little tricky but pretty soon,

00:17:29.880 --> 00:17:34.720
by about 1991 we started to
find all kinds of fossils.

00:17:34.720 --> 00:17:35.990
I mean the first things we started to see

00:17:35.990 --> 00:17:37.870
were like teeth the
size of railroad spikes

00:17:37.870 --> 00:17:39.750
coming out of the hills here.

00:17:39.750 --> 00:17:41.400
We started to find jaws
to these creatures.

00:17:41.400 --> 00:17:44.600
This is Ted holding one
of our first jaws we found

00:17:44.600 --> 00:17:45.450
out of this thing.

00:17:45.450 --> 00:17:46.970
It was just the front end of the jaw.

00:17:46.970 --> 00:17:49.004
These jaws are like long as your arm

00:17:49.004 --> 00:17:51.400
and you know with teeth
the size of your thumb.

00:17:51.400 --> 00:17:53.300
So these are really big monstrous fish

00:17:53.300 --> 00:17:56.810
that are about 16 feet
long, up to 16 feet long.

00:17:56.810 --> 00:18:00.640
So large carnivorous fish
coming out of the rocks here.

00:18:00.640 --> 00:18:03.569
We have lots of other kinds
of fish, invertebrate animals.

00:18:03.569 --> 00:18:07.010
This is the sidewall of a fish,
you can see its body armor,

00:18:07.010 --> 00:18:08.760
it's got a squashed head here.

00:18:08.760 --> 00:18:10.440
Tons of these kinds of things.

00:18:10.440 --> 00:18:13.760
And then by about 1993 we started to find

00:18:13.760 --> 00:18:17.680
bits and pieces of early limbed animals.

00:18:17.680 --> 00:18:18.880
And this was one that was particularly

00:18:18.880 --> 00:18:20.250
important at the time.

00:18:20.250 --> 00:18:22.340
It's an upper arm bone, the humerus,

00:18:22.340 --> 00:18:24.350
and we started to find a femur,

00:18:24.350 --> 00:18:25.670
which is an upper leg bone.

00:18:25.670 --> 00:18:27.840
We found other bones of
the skull and so forth.

00:18:27.840 --> 00:18:29.770
And this humerus is particularly important

00:18:29.770 --> 00:18:34.380
because it was very similar
to a humerus known from

00:18:34.380 --> 00:18:37.297
a Devonian limbed animal from Greenland.

00:18:37.297 --> 00:18:40.210
The one actually I showed
you in a cartoon earlier.

00:18:40.210 --> 00:18:41.150
So it was pretty successful.

00:18:41.150 --> 00:18:43.780
We started to find by the mid-90s,

00:18:43.780 --> 00:18:45.010
a whole ecosystem really.

00:18:45.010 --> 00:18:46.710
And I'm not describing the plants.

00:18:46.710 --> 00:18:48.290
Some of the earliest known forests,

00:18:48.290 --> 00:18:52.080
with trees, we found their
leaves and trunks and so forth.

00:18:52.080 --> 00:18:54.820
Land was loaded with lots of life,

00:18:54.820 --> 00:18:56.900
scorpion-like and spider-like creatures,

00:18:56.900 --> 00:18:58.710
and many of those from these sites,

00:18:58.710 --> 00:19:01.350
and then tons of fish from within here.

00:19:01.350 --> 00:19:03.130
And this is what this road cut,

00:19:03.130 --> 00:19:05.090
Red Hill road cut in
Pennsylvania looked like

00:19:05.090 --> 00:19:08.010
when we reconstructed it
with National Geographic.

00:19:08.010 --> 00:19:09.330
You know you got that large fish,

00:19:09.330 --> 00:19:11.400
you know with the teeth the
size of railroad spikes.

00:19:11.400 --> 00:19:14.220
You have lots of little
armored fish around here,

00:19:14.220 --> 00:19:16.320
and then you had these limbed animals

00:19:16.320 --> 00:19:18.900
with the tetrapods, literally
four legged creatures

00:19:18.900 --> 00:19:20.990
of which there are about
three or four types

00:19:20.990 --> 00:19:21.823
coming out of here.

00:19:21.823 --> 00:19:23.063
It's really remarkable.

00:19:24.250 --> 00:19:25.870
But it became really clear

00:19:25.870 --> 00:19:27.180
that to get to the problem

00:19:27.180 --> 00:19:29.500
that I was interested in,

00:19:29.500 --> 00:19:32.800
this transition, we weren't
making a ton of headway.

00:19:32.800 --> 00:19:34.460
We were finding tons of fossils,

00:19:34.460 --> 00:19:37.240
but these rocks are about
365 million years old.

00:19:37.240 --> 00:19:38.800
And what we were picking up at this point

00:19:38.800 --> 00:19:42.060
were mostly really well formed tetrapods.

00:19:42.060 --> 00:19:45.090
We were picking up some of
these creatures as well.

00:19:45.090 --> 00:19:46.850
But from our knowledge of the rocks

00:19:46.850 --> 00:19:49.210
and faunas around the
world, it was pretty clear

00:19:49.210 --> 00:19:51.230
we were probably in rocks too young.

00:19:51.230 --> 00:19:53.070
We would have to move back in time.

00:19:53.070 --> 00:19:54.350
Because to move back in time,

00:19:54.350 --> 00:19:56.150
we begin to understand
some of the transition here

00:19:56.150 --> 00:19:56.983
and I just want to run through

00:19:56.983 --> 00:19:58.960
some of the anatomy that's different.

00:19:58.960 --> 00:20:00.920
And here you see the
lobe-finned fish on top,

00:20:00.920 --> 00:20:03.555
which we knew was closely
related to limbed animals.

00:20:03.555 --> 00:20:04.720
And just look at the head.

00:20:04.720 --> 00:20:08.030
You see basic differences in
the architecture of the head.

00:20:08.030 --> 00:20:09.480
You know here at the top you see,

00:20:09.480 --> 00:20:11.880
you know these creatures
have like a conical head

00:20:11.880 --> 00:20:13.090
with eyes on either side.

00:20:13.090 --> 00:20:15.397
The early limbed animals have got

00:20:15.397 --> 00:20:17.570
almost like a crocodilian kind of head.

00:20:17.570 --> 00:20:20.280
It's a flat head with eyes on top.

00:20:20.280 --> 00:20:22.180
And the architecture of the bones in here

00:20:22.180 --> 00:20:24.310
actually is somewhat different

00:20:25.496 --> 00:20:27.570
than the fish on top as well.

00:20:27.570 --> 00:20:29.220
If you look at the neck,
fish don't have a neck.

00:20:29.220 --> 00:20:30.220
Again as I said before,

00:20:30.220 --> 00:20:32.510
the head is actually
connected to the shoulder

00:20:32.510 --> 00:20:34.773
via sort of linkages of bones

00:20:34.773 --> 00:20:37.340
and the head is not independent movable,

00:20:37.340 --> 00:20:38.760
whereas in early limbed animals,

00:20:38.760 --> 00:20:39.910
like all their descendants,

00:20:39.910 --> 00:20:41.090
you and I,

00:20:41.090 --> 00:20:42.530
have a neck with a head that's
separate from the shoulder

00:20:42.530 --> 00:20:46.463
and there's a series of joints
at the base of the skull.

00:20:47.680 --> 00:20:49.624
And you know finally, and I
can make a long list here,

00:20:49.624 --> 00:20:51.860
the thing that was
really interesting to me

00:20:51.860 --> 00:20:54.630
was to understand the
shift from fins to limbs.

00:20:54.630 --> 00:20:56.570
Fish had fins with fin webbing,

00:20:56.570 --> 00:20:57.640
you lose the fin webbing

00:20:57.640 --> 00:20:59.350
when you get to these
early limbed animals,

00:20:59.350 --> 00:21:02.870
and you gain fingers and toes
and wrists and ankles okay.

00:21:02.870 --> 00:21:04.550
And we weren't making
a whole ton of headway

00:21:04.550 --> 00:21:06.270
in understanding this transition.

00:21:06.270 --> 00:21:08.230
And it became very clear from what we knew

00:21:08.230 --> 00:21:10.010
and this is what we were finding.

00:21:10.010 --> 00:21:11.990
This is the family tree more or less.

00:21:11.990 --> 00:21:13.820
Here's limbed animals up here.

00:21:13.820 --> 00:21:15.270
These are the fish that are successfully

00:21:15.270 --> 00:21:16.860
mostly related to them.

00:21:16.860 --> 00:21:17.980
If we wanted to make any headway,

00:21:17.980 --> 00:21:19.400
we had to find creatures that were sort of

00:21:19.400 --> 00:21:20.430
more on this branch,

00:21:20.430 --> 00:21:22.790
which would really be able to very clearly

00:21:22.790 --> 00:21:24.750
tell us the sequence of keys

00:21:24.750 --> 00:21:27.160
or the origin of key features

00:21:27.160 --> 00:21:29.800
that led to the origin of limbed animals.

00:21:29.800 --> 00:21:31.120
And to do that,

00:21:31.120 --> 00:21:33.510
when we look at the age of these things,

00:21:33.510 --> 00:21:35.300
these things, many of these first appear

00:21:35.300 --> 00:21:37.820
back around 380, 390 million years ago.

00:21:37.820 --> 00:21:39.660
Some of them continue all the way up.

00:21:39.660 --> 00:21:41.960
The earliest limbed animals, tetrapods,

00:21:41.960 --> 00:21:45.270
appeared around 363,
365 million years ago,

00:21:45.270 --> 00:21:46.480
the good scalable material.

00:21:46.480 --> 00:21:48.420
At the time, that's what we knew.

00:21:48.420 --> 00:21:49.930
But there is a big gap in our knowledge.

00:21:49.930 --> 00:21:53.070
We didn't have many faunas
or floras at this age

00:21:53.070 --> 00:21:55.750
really here about 375 million years ago.

00:21:55.750 --> 00:21:57.913
So we had to move back in time.

00:21:59.270 --> 00:22:00.710
And so we began our hunt again right.

00:22:00.710 --> 00:22:03.250
So you look, remember we\
look for rocks the right age,

00:22:03.250 --> 00:22:05.210
rocks the right type and exposures.

00:22:05.210 --> 00:22:07.010
And going through it,
it became pretty clear

00:22:07.010 --> 00:22:09.790
we had to, we were thinking
about going to Brazil,

00:22:09.790 --> 00:22:11.890
we were thinking about
working in Colorado.

00:22:11.890 --> 00:22:14.760
Everything changed for us one
day in the winter of 1998,

00:22:14.760 --> 00:22:17.240
in my office at the
University Of Pennsylvania.

00:22:17.240 --> 00:22:18.630
Ted and I were having an argument

00:22:18.630 --> 00:22:20.750
and to settle the argument, I pulled out

00:22:20.750 --> 00:22:23.844
a college undergraduate
geology textbook. (laughs)

00:22:23.844 --> 00:22:26.350
This is I think, the one that
I had was the second edition

00:22:26.350 --> 00:22:27.930
of Dott and Batten,
Evolution Of The Earth.

00:22:27.930 --> 00:22:30.440
I believed it was pre-plate
tectonic when it was written.

00:22:30.440 --> 00:22:32.160
This book is now I think
in the 11th edition

00:22:32.160 --> 00:22:33.370
or something like that.

00:22:33.370 --> 00:22:34.360
We settled the debate

00:22:34.360 --> 00:22:35.988
and as I was thumbing through the book,

00:22:35.988 --> 00:22:40.100
after that little set to,

00:22:40.100 --> 00:22:43.780
I came upon this figure in the
textbook in like chapter 14.

00:22:43.780 --> 00:22:45.680
And it stopped me in my tracks

00:22:45.680 --> 00:22:47.610
and basically defined my research,

00:22:47.610 --> 00:22:49.650
at least in the field
for the next six years.

00:22:49.650 --> 00:22:51.520
So I want to spend a
second on this diagram,

00:22:51.520 --> 00:22:53.080
it's that important.

00:22:53.080 --> 00:22:55.330
It says, Upper Devonian
Sedimentary Facies.

00:22:55.330 --> 00:22:57.162
Which means, you know rocks
more of less the right age

00:22:57.162 --> 00:22:58.700
and you know maybe
rocks of the right type.

00:22:58.700 --> 00:23:01.380
And what you see here is
a map of North America,

00:23:01.380 --> 00:23:04.090
here's the United States, here's Mexico,

00:23:04.090 --> 00:23:06.340
here's Canada, Greenland, Canadian Arctic.

00:23:06.340 --> 00:23:07.740
And superimposed on that,

00:23:07.740 --> 00:23:09.680
is a map of the depositional environments,

00:23:09.680 --> 00:23:13.150
or the environments of rock
formation in the Devonian.

00:23:13.150 --> 00:23:15.890
And the western part of North America

00:23:15.890 --> 00:23:17.563
was mapped as an ancient ocean.

00:23:19.140 --> 00:23:20.980
The rocks there were formed,
the Devonian at least,

00:23:20.980 --> 00:23:22.570
were formed in the ancient ocean.

00:23:22.570 --> 00:23:25.390
But these authors, Dott and Batten,

00:23:25.390 --> 00:23:26.460
with their citations,

00:23:26.460 --> 00:23:28.630
identified three areas around the world

00:23:28.630 --> 00:23:30.820
that were formed in ancient Delta systems,

00:23:30.820 --> 00:23:33.130
like the Amazon Delta today.

00:23:33.130 --> 00:23:35.234
One of them, the first one
I showed and right here,

00:23:35.234 --> 00:23:36.500
we know about that one right,

00:23:36.500 --> 00:23:37.840
that's the Catskill project.

00:23:37.840 --> 00:23:39.310
That's where Ted and
I were already working

00:23:39.310 --> 00:23:40.383
and finding fossils.

00:23:42.030 --> 00:23:44.710
The second one is up in Greenland,

00:23:44.710 --> 00:23:45.900
this is East Greenland,

00:23:45.900 --> 00:23:48.500
I already showed you a
limbed animal form there.

00:23:48.500 --> 00:23:49.680
This is well known.

00:23:49.680 --> 00:23:52.020
But there's a third area
that stopped me in my tracks,

00:23:52.020 --> 00:23:54.690
and it's an area extending
about 1500 kilometers

00:23:54.690 --> 00:23:57.620
east to west across the Canadian Arctic,

00:23:57.620 --> 00:24:00.130
which was mapped by
these guys and said to be

00:24:00.130 --> 00:24:02.480
Devonian Age rocks,
like Devonian Age rocks,

00:24:02.480 --> 00:24:04.590
formed in ancient delta systems,

00:24:04.590 --> 00:24:06.430
completely unexplored.

00:24:06.430 --> 00:24:08.840
And that, you know, that
literally stopped us.

00:24:08.840 --> 00:24:12.150
So we ran to the library, and
this all happened one morning.

00:24:12.150 --> 00:24:13.510
Ran to the library,

00:24:13.510 --> 00:24:15.570
and there we started to uncover

00:24:15.570 --> 00:24:16.750
a really wonderful story.

00:24:16.750 --> 00:24:17.840
And just indulge me

00:24:17.840 --> 00:24:20.990
as I spend a second or
two on this little story.

00:24:20.990 --> 00:24:25.500
The story begins in 1890s in Norway

00:24:25.500 --> 00:24:29.810
where the Norwegians wanted
to run to the North Pole.

00:24:29.810 --> 00:24:31.460
There's a race to get to the North Pole.

00:24:31.460 --> 00:24:33.250
And the Norwegians had
a really bright idea

00:24:33.250 --> 00:24:35.950
to design a ship, a
really strong wooden boat,

00:24:35.950 --> 00:24:40.050
and that this wooden boat
would be sitting in the Arctic

00:24:40.050 --> 00:24:42.450
and get carried by currents
up to the North Pole.

00:24:42.450 --> 00:24:43.490
That was their idea.

00:24:43.490 --> 00:24:44.720
And they had an explorer named Nansen

00:24:44.720 --> 00:24:46.840
who was a remarkable
individual in many ways,

00:24:46.840 --> 00:24:48.990
who helped design this boat.

00:24:48.990 --> 00:24:50.140
And this boat's called the Fram,

00:24:50.140 --> 00:24:52.190
which means forward in Norwegian,

00:24:52.190 --> 00:24:54.040
and it's truly a remarkable ship.

00:24:54.040 --> 00:24:56.492
This is a boat that took
Nansen furthest North,

00:24:56.492 --> 00:24:57.325
it didn't get him to the North Pole

00:24:57.325 --> 00:25:00.050
but it got him close in the 1890s,

00:25:00.050 --> 00:25:01.930
it was eventually to take Amundsen

00:25:01.930 --> 00:25:04.510
to the South Pole around 1910,

00:25:04.510 --> 00:25:06.600
so it went from north to south.

00:25:06.600 --> 00:25:09.090
In the interim, it went
to the Canadian Arctic

00:25:09.090 --> 00:25:10.480
with this crew.

00:25:10.480 --> 00:25:12.700
And this is the crew led by Otto Sverdrup,

00:25:12.700 --> 00:25:15.329
he doesn't look like
he's a very funny guy,

00:25:15.329 --> 00:25:17.080
but you know what they did

00:25:17.080 --> 00:25:18.810
was for three or four years,

00:25:18.810 --> 00:25:21.060
they went up to the Canadian Arctic

00:25:21.060 --> 00:25:22.940
overwintered there on the ship,

00:25:22.940 --> 00:25:25.180
the sole purpose being to understand

00:25:25.180 --> 00:25:28.930
the flora, the fauna, and the
rocks of the Canadian Arctic.

00:25:28.930 --> 00:25:31.440
On the boat was this
gentleman here, Per Schei,

00:25:31.440 --> 00:25:33.585
he's the hero of the story.

00:25:33.585 --> 00:25:34.460
So what they did was,

00:25:34.460 --> 00:25:36.690
they went to Southern Ellesmere Island,

00:25:36.690 --> 00:25:39.790
from 1898 to 1902.

00:25:39.790 --> 00:25:42.650
And they went to these fjords
down here overwintering,

00:25:42.650 --> 00:25:44.100
and it's a pretty harsh
place to overwinter,

00:25:44.100 --> 00:25:46.100
I can tell you that much.

00:25:46.100 --> 00:25:47.590
And Schei would get off the boat

00:25:47.590 --> 00:25:49.173
and start mapping the geology.

00:25:50.060 --> 00:25:51.346
This is Per Schei.

00:25:51.346 --> 00:25:54.200
He started mapping the
geology and you can see,

00:25:54.200 --> 00:25:56.650
here's a fjord he went
to called Goose Fjord,

00:25:56.650 --> 00:25:57.850
and he started mapping it out

00:25:57.850 --> 00:26:01.600
and he started to pull out bones of fish.

00:26:01.600 --> 00:26:02.760
And these were the species of fish,

00:26:02.760 --> 00:26:05.270
the fauna list that he brought about.

00:26:05.270 --> 00:26:08.280
Little pieces, rhino
flex and this and that.

00:26:08.280 --> 00:26:09.790
This was actually to be lost.

00:26:09.790 --> 00:26:11.070
No one really was to cite this.

00:26:11.070 --> 00:26:14.200
Per Schei passed away tragically

00:26:14.200 --> 00:26:15.813
after the return of the Fram,

00:26:15.813 --> 00:26:17.915
he died at age 30.

00:26:17.915 --> 00:26:20.500
And this work was
subsequently just picked up

00:26:20.500 --> 00:26:22.130
by a guy named Keran in 1915,

00:26:22.130 --> 00:26:23.670
who described it and then this paper

00:26:23.670 --> 00:26:24.770
sort of sat in the literature,

00:26:24.770 --> 00:26:28.960
never really, never
really cited until 1974.

00:26:28.960 --> 00:26:31.270
This gentleman comes along, Ashton Embry,

00:26:31.270 --> 00:26:34.730
who mapped, who was partly
responsible for running

00:26:34.730 --> 00:26:37.210
a mapping project in the Canadian Arctic,

00:26:37.210 --> 00:26:38.760
mapping the rocks of the Arctic

00:26:38.760 --> 00:26:40.460
for a variety of economic reasons.

00:26:41.450 --> 00:26:43.660
And what Ashton did,
is a map in the Arctic,

00:26:43.660 --> 00:26:46.240
he really did a precise
map which basically told us

00:26:46.240 --> 00:26:47.230
that we had to work there,

00:26:47.230 --> 00:26:48.487
and where we had to work.

00:26:48.487 --> 00:26:51.050
And the paper that did it is this,

00:26:51.050 --> 00:26:53.200
and it was published in 1976.

00:26:53.200 --> 00:26:55.090
And the reason why I'm
showing you this paper

00:26:55.090 --> 00:26:57.530
is there's a single page in the paper

00:26:57.530 --> 00:26:59.320
that basically told us we had to go

00:26:59.320 --> 00:27:01.140
immediately to the Canadian Arctic.

00:27:01.140 --> 00:27:02.800
And this is the page.

00:27:02.800 --> 00:27:04.800
It doesn't look like much,
a lot of words on the page,

00:27:04.800 --> 00:27:06.330
but I'll blow up two areas for you.

00:27:06.330 --> 00:27:09.830
Where he talks about
age, blow it up it says,

00:27:09.830 --> 00:27:11.440
the available data indicate an age

00:27:11.440 --> 00:27:13.150
of Early to Middle Frannian.

00:27:13.150 --> 00:27:15.490
You remember the question
mark I showed you before,

00:27:15.490 --> 00:27:17.520
that's the question mark.

00:27:17.520 --> 00:27:20.980
Then it really, where we lost it, (laughs)

00:27:20.980 --> 00:27:22.850
was essentially when we saw

00:27:22.850 --> 00:27:25.050
what he described as the Fram Formation.

00:27:25.050 --> 00:27:26.250
The Fram Formation is similar

00:27:26.250 --> 00:27:28.850
to the Catskill Formation of Pennsylvania.

00:27:28.850 --> 00:27:31.510
So here we had rocks at the question mark

00:27:31.510 --> 00:27:34.020
that were similar to the Catskill
Formation of Pennsylvania.

00:27:34.020 --> 00:27:36.100
This all happened in the morning in 1998,

00:27:36.100 --> 00:27:39.557
in you know, in my office in a library

00:27:39.557 --> 00:27:41.090
at the University of Pennsylvania.

00:27:41.090 --> 00:27:42.840
We were shaking, there was
nothing else we could do,

00:27:42.840 --> 00:27:44.780
we went to get some Chinese food.

00:27:44.780 --> 00:27:47.220
So um, we went for Chinese food,

00:27:47.220 --> 00:27:48.730
I had my kung pao chicken,

00:27:48.730 --> 00:27:49.860
and this really sealed the deal.

00:27:49.860 --> 00:27:51.216
I opened my fortune cookie,

00:27:51.216 --> 00:27:52.870
and it said,

00:27:52.870 --> 00:27:54.859
soon you will be at the top of the world.

00:27:54.859 --> 00:27:56.420
(laughing)

00:27:56.420 --> 00:27:57.860
So I was like, okay we're out of here.

00:27:57.860 --> 00:28:00.810
Anyway so that got us there.

00:28:00.810 --> 00:28:04.150
So um, so this is what,

00:28:04.150 --> 00:28:05.118
so we're dealing with Nunavut territory,

00:28:05.118 --> 00:28:06.800
here's the North Pole,

00:28:06.800 --> 00:28:09.820
we're 600 miles or 700
miles from the North Pole,

00:28:09.820 --> 00:28:12.510
this is Ellesmere Island
right here, here's Ellesmere.

00:28:12.510 --> 00:28:16.730
This is what Ashton maps
as the exposures of the,

00:28:16.730 --> 00:28:18.590
of the Devonian the Canadian Arctic.

00:28:18.590 --> 00:28:19.930
He named the key formation,

00:28:19.930 --> 00:28:22.000
the one that's most like
the Catskill Formation,

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:23.440
after that boat The Fram,

00:28:23.440 --> 00:28:25.630
and it's called the Fram
Formation right here.

00:28:25.630 --> 00:28:27.490
So it's actually right at that right edge,

00:28:27.490 --> 00:28:28.323
the question mark.

00:28:28.323 --> 00:28:30.710
The earliest-known tetrapods,
limbed animals at the time,

00:28:30.710 --> 00:28:31.660
were from up here,

00:28:31.660 --> 00:28:34.290
so we're significantly earlier in time.

00:28:34.290 --> 00:28:35.640
And again just to show you the cartoon,

00:28:35.640 --> 00:28:37.370
he mapped it as a Delta system,

00:28:37.370 --> 00:28:39.860
with a series of Highlands
to the east and north,

00:28:39.860 --> 00:28:41.200
and Inland Sea to the west,

00:28:41.200 --> 00:28:42.770
and the series of streams and rivers

00:28:42.770 --> 00:28:43.810
draining from east to west,

00:28:43.810 --> 00:28:44.643
so off we go.

00:28:44.643 --> 00:28:45.964
It was a little bit of challenge because

00:28:45.964 --> 00:28:47.870
the places up there right,

00:28:47.870 --> 00:28:50.160
it's not here where I could
drive with my Subaru to,

00:28:50.160 --> 00:28:51.170
you know Pennsylvania,

00:28:51.170 --> 00:28:54.060
it's up here which creates problems,

00:28:54.060 --> 00:28:56.628
I mean logistic problems.

00:28:56.628 --> 00:28:59.230
So the nearest town to us
where we ended up working,

00:28:59.230 --> 00:29:00.750
is a couple hundred miles away,

00:29:00.750 --> 00:29:02.440
and this is a picture of that town,

00:29:02.440 --> 00:29:06.540
with a population of about
170 people in spring.

00:29:06.540 --> 00:29:08.960
It's Grise Fjord, Grise Fjord, Nunavut.

00:29:08.960 --> 00:29:10.850
It's not, you know, not
a hotbed of activity.

00:29:10.850 --> 00:29:13.910
So it's quite remote you know,

00:29:13.910 --> 00:29:17.210
so everything we bring is fairly precious,

00:29:17.210 --> 00:29:19.233
we bring a small crew as
I'll show you in a second,

00:29:19.233 --> 00:29:22.710
because we get around
through this ferry operation

00:29:22.710 --> 00:29:24.920
of helicopters and planes since we're so,

00:29:24.920 --> 00:29:26.440
we're farther than a tank of gas

00:29:26.440 --> 00:29:27.970
could take us in a helicopter,

00:29:27.970 --> 00:29:29.672
so fuel has to be ferried in to get us

00:29:29.672 --> 00:29:31.180
to where we want to go.

00:29:31.180 --> 00:29:33.070
So we take these planes
which land actually

00:29:33.070 --> 00:29:34.320
on the rock and Tundra here,

00:29:34.320 --> 00:29:36.133
it's pretty thrilling actually,

00:29:36.133 --> 00:29:38.710
and then, if you define that term loosely,

00:29:38.710 --> 00:29:42.410
and then the helicopters
take us into our camps.

00:29:42.410 --> 00:29:44.310
Because of that it really
affects the science we can do,

00:29:44.310 --> 00:29:46.725
we can't bring big crews and importantly,

00:29:46.725 --> 00:29:48.840
when we find something,

00:29:48.840 --> 00:29:50.910
and ie fossils, which are very heavy,

00:29:50.910 --> 00:29:52.510
we can't bring a lot of them back.

00:29:52.510 --> 00:29:54.700
And so we leave a lot of
what we find out there,

00:29:54.700 --> 00:29:56.270
and we, you know it's a real decision.

00:29:56.270 --> 00:29:57.740
We're out there for five or six weeks,

00:29:57.740 --> 00:30:00.740
and we're making sort of,
hard choices about what stays

00:30:00.740 --> 00:30:02.003
and what comes with us.

00:30:03.430 --> 00:30:07.240
So we started in 1990, the
fortune cookie was in 1998,

00:30:07.240 --> 00:30:09.040
it took us about a year to raise money,

00:30:09.040 --> 00:30:11.403
and so we went to the western
part of the Arctic first,

00:30:11.403 --> 00:30:12.643
this is what camp looks like,

00:30:12.643 --> 00:30:14.660
it's the personal tents, main tent.

00:30:14.660 --> 00:30:16.840
What we do is basically,
these are the Devonian rocks,

00:30:16.840 --> 00:30:19.210
and since you have this
freeze thaw in the Arctic,

00:30:19.210 --> 00:30:22.730
the bones come weathering
out, quite nicely.

00:30:22.730 --> 00:30:24.470
And you know we walk over the rocks,

00:30:24.470 --> 00:30:25.480
and when you find bones,

00:30:25.480 --> 00:30:27.790
you look for the layers
that they're coming from.

00:30:27.790 --> 00:30:30.720
In 1999 we didn't find much,
we had terrible weather,

00:30:30.720 --> 00:30:32.575
and it turns out we were
actually in much deeper

00:30:32.575 --> 00:30:35.890
ocean ancient deeper ocean,
than we wanted to be.

00:30:35.890 --> 00:30:38.750
So following the Delta model,
we had to move upstream,

00:30:38.750 --> 00:30:41.500
and what that meant
geologically, is moving east.

00:30:41.500 --> 00:30:44.700
And when we moved east to
southern Ellesmere Island here,

00:30:44.700 --> 00:30:48.790
that's when we started to
find lobe-finned in abundance,

00:30:48.790 --> 00:30:50.080
bits and pieces of them at least,

00:30:50.080 --> 00:30:51.470
along these sort of cliff things,

00:30:51.470 --> 00:30:53.233
as we walk up and down the cliffs.

00:30:55.060 --> 00:30:57.710
The big discovery was made by

00:30:57.710 --> 00:31:00.160
a college undergraduate Jason Downes,

00:31:00.160 --> 00:31:02.740
who joined us one year
to sort of apprentice.

00:31:02.740 --> 00:31:05.804
This is the site Jason was to discover

00:31:05.804 --> 00:31:08.370
in the morning before he discovered it.

00:31:08.370 --> 00:31:09.660
So about three hours later,

00:31:09.660 --> 00:31:10.780
Ted took this picture.

00:31:10.780 --> 00:31:13.220
About three hours later Jason was to walk

00:31:13.220 --> 00:31:15.383
over this little patch here, I
don't know if you can see it,

00:31:15.383 --> 00:31:19.630
it's sort of a greenish gray patch.

00:31:19.630 --> 00:31:21.150
We didn't know it at the time,

00:31:21.150 --> 00:31:22.890
but Jason had discovered,

00:31:22.890 --> 00:31:24.900
an enormous quantity of bone.

00:31:24.900 --> 00:31:27.310
He was late back to camp, it
was actually quite a worry,

00:31:27.310 --> 00:31:30.520
but he returned to camp with
pile after pile of bone.

00:31:30.520 --> 00:31:31.700
So what we did that night was,

00:31:31.700 --> 00:31:33.710
since it's daylight 24
hours a day in the Arctic,

00:31:33.710 --> 00:31:35.370
this is us that night around midnight

00:31:35.370 --> 00:31:36.610
or 1:00 in the morning,

00:31:36.610 --> 00:31:38.863
actually crawling Jason's site,

00:31:40.290 --> 00:31:43.330
to find the layer that Jason's
bones were coming from.

00:31:43.330 --> 00:31:47.520
Now this grayish green
carpet here was formed,

00:31:47.520 --> 00:31:48.730
I mean I should say a carpet,

00:31:48.730 --> 00:31:51.190
of thousands and thousands
and thousands of fish bones

00:31:51.190 --> 00:31:53.290
of which you're seeing
like lungfish tooth plates,

00:31:53.290 --> 00:31:55.160
and things like that here.

00:31:55.160 --> 00:31:57.790
It took us about a year I
should say, I mean a whole year,

00:31:57.790 --> 00:32:00.150
to actually find that layer,
it was actually quite hard,

00:32:00.150 --> 00:32:03.030
but when we found it, we
were able to isolate it,

00:32:03.030 --> 00:32:04.530
this is Ted here and the crew,

00:32:06.550 --> 00:32:11.370
the layer was exposed as
a series of fish skeletons

00:32:11.370 --> 00:32:13.230
buried one on top of the other.

00:32:13.230 --> 00:32:15.520
So Jason's little carpet of fish fragments

00:32:15.520 --> 00:32:16.840
was formed by skeletons,

00:32:16.840 --> 00:32:18.360
mostly you know half skeletons,

00:32:18.360 --> 00:32:19.930
occasionally a full skeleton,

00:32:19.930 --> 00:32:23.440
but it was really articulated
material that was coming out.

00:32:23.440 --> 00:32:25.120
So we opened up the hole fairly large,

00:32:25.120 --> 00:32:27.126
and this is what it looked like

00:32:27.126 --> 00:32:29.422
in 2006 actually after a while,

00:32:29.422 --> 00:32:30.930
and the big discovery happened here,

00:32:30.930 --> 00:32:32.940
with the my colleague Steve Gatesy

00:32:32.940 --> 00:32:35.000
who was cracking rock and discovered this,

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:36.280
I don't know if you're going to see it

00:32:36.280 --> 00:32:38.560
but you the Devonian rock here,

00:32:38.560 --> 00:32:41.470
see this little V and
there's a little slash there.

00:32:41.470 --> 00:32:43.090
This little V, he said,
"Hey guys what's this?"

00:32:43.090 --> 00:32:46.360
We looked at it, turns out
it's the snout of a fish,

00:32:46.360 --> 00:32:49.090
and not just any fish, a flat-headed fish.

00:32:49.090 --> 00:32:50.180
You could tell it was flat-headed snout.

00:32:50.180 --> 00:32:51.420
So remember I showed you before,

00:32:51.420 --> 00:32:52.600
conical head, flat head?

00:32:52.600 --> 00:32:54.880
Here I had a flat head
sticking out of the cliff,

00:32:54.880 --> 00:32:56.360
looking me in the eye right.

00:32:56.360 --> 00:32:58.660
So I kind of knew we'd found
what we were looking for.

00:32:58.660 --> 00:33:00.090
And so what it became then,

00:33:00.090 --> 00:33:02.380
was to remove these things very carefully.

00:33:02.380 --> 00:33:04.350
As we remove this one,
we found about four more

00:33:04.350 --> 00:33:07.380
of these flat headed fish,
we now have about 20 of them,

00:33:07.380 --> 00:33:08.880
in various states,

00:33:08.880 --> 00:33:10.760
from individual bones to whole skeletons,

00:33:10.760 --> 00:33:12.560
to the skeletons we have about five.

00:33:14.200 --> 00:33:16.050
So come home on the bottom
of the helicopter anyway.

00:33:16.050 --> 00:33:18.507
So when these came back,
it was in the fall of 2005,

00:33:18.507 --> 00:33:20.450
the preparators take
over and these are people

00:33:20.450 --> 00:33:22.120
who work with a needle and pin,

00:33:22.120 --> 00:33:25.200
and these things come
back encased in plaster.

00:33:25.200 --> 00:33:26.580
And this is Steve's specimen,

