00:37:09.830 --> 00:37:10.830
and here's a shoulder.

00:37:10.830 --> 00:37:12.271
And so we took all these things out

00:37:12.271 --> 00:37:14.510
and we were really fortunate in that

00:37:14.510 --> 00:37:17.480
not only did we have many of
the bones of the of the fin,

00:37:17.480 --> 00:37:19.060
so you take off the fin webbing,

00:37:19.060 --> 00:37:20.370
this thing had fin webbing,

00:37:20.370 --> 00:37:22.480
and then you see, just like our arm,

00:37:22.480 --> 00:37:23.950
if you were look at your
own arm in the skeleton,

00:37:23.950 --> 00:37:25.570
you have one bone, upper arm bone,

00:37:25.570 --> 00:37:27.350
two bones in the forearm,

00:37:27.350 --> 00:37:30.340
a series of joints here,
that as they go distally,

00:37:30.340 --> 00:37:31.527
they can flex and extend,

00:37:31.527 --> 00:37:34.150
and those joints go all the
way out to your fingers.

00:37:34.150 --> 00:37:35.450
And that's essentially what you have here.

00:37:35.450 --> 00:37:38.740
One bone, two bones, you
have a series of joints

00:37:38.740 --> 00:37:39.657
that are capable of flexion,

00:37:39.657 --> 00:37:42.000
just like like your wrists and fingers.

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:44.200
And indeed, we can compare these bones,

00:37:44.200 --> 00:37:45.610
this bone here and this bone here,

00:37:45.610 --> 00:37:48.120
to bones that are actually in amphibians,

00:37:48.120 --> 00:37:50.120
creatures for lack of a better word.

