00:38:13.150 --> 00:38:15.420
Very unusual shoulder in
some ways, it has a ball,

00:38:15.420 --> 00:38:17.230
but has a sort of cam-stop here,

00:38:17.230 --> 00:38:19.980
which would prevent it from
this action of protraction.

00:38:22.448 --> 00:38:23.780
We could see the elbow of Tiktaalik.

00:38:23.780 --> 00:38:26.550
Here's the radius and here's the ulna,

00:38:26.550 --> 00:38:27.950
and you can see the sockets,

00:38:27.950 --> 00:38:31.263
where they'd fit on the elbow
joint of the distal humerus.

00:38:31.263 --> 00:38:33.650
This is the arm bone and you
can see where they'd fit on,

00:38:33.650 --> 00:38:35.480
and you can see how this one facet,

00:38:35.480 --> 00:38:39.060
which sort of rotates
this down this side here.

00:38:39.060 --> 00:38:41.060
That means this bone could rotate far down

00:38:41.060 --> 00:38:43.203
into the plane of the
slide, that's important,

00:38:43.203 --> 00:38:44.650
I'll show you later.

00:38:44.650 --> 00:38:46.690
And then we can do it for
every other joint in the thing.

00:38:46.690 --> 00:38:48.440
It was really remarkable
to be able to do that,

00:38:48.440 --> 00:38:51.090
and what we're doing now is
actually modeling it digitally,

00:38:51.090 --> 00:38:53.600
to see how these bones
would move on one another.

00:38:53.600 --> 00:38:54.620
But to give you a sense of all this,

00:38:54.620 --> 00:38:55.500
let's just look at the shoulder.

00:38:55.500 --> 00:38:57.339
And I have three creatures here.

00:38:57.339 --> 00:38:59.070
I have one, a lobe-finned fish,

00:38:59.070 --> 00:39:00.940
this is a Eusthenopteron,

00:39:00.940 --> 00:39:03.460
here's an early limbed
animal Acanthostega,

00:39:03.460 --> 00:39:07.030
and you're seeing the shoulders
here from from the side.

00:39:07.030 --> 00:39:08.700
Okay so you're like looking at the animal

00:39:08.700 --> 00:39:10.320
from the side like this,

00:39:10.320 --> 00:39:11.580
and here's Tiktaalik.

00:39:11.580 --> 00:39:13.440
One of the things is, you
can see the shoulder socket,

00:39:13.440 --> 00:39:16.740
here in Acanthostega and you
can't see it in Eusthenopteron.

00:39:16.740 --> 00:39:17.770
Well if you pop on the humerus

00:39:17.770 --> 00:39:18.760
you can see the upper arm bone

00:39:18.760 --> 00:39:19.610
you can see what that means.

00:39:19.610 --> 00:39:23.040
In Acanthostega, this early limbed animal,

00:39:23.040 --> 00:39:26.280
the humerus or upper arm
bone is coming out at you,

00:39:26.280 --> 00:39:29.769
like this, like a crocodile,
so the limb is held

00:39:29.769 --> 00:39:31.890
to the side of the body.

00:39:31.890 --> 00:39:33.943
Whereas in fish like Eusthenopteron,

00:39:35.219 --> 00:39:38.723
the humerus is facing backwards like this.

00:39:39.608 --> 00:39:41.740
In Tiktaalik it's different it's rotated,

00:39:41.740 --> 00:39:43.110
that whole joint is rotated,

00:39:43.110 --> 00:39:44.770
so it's sort of intermediate in position

00:39:44.770 --> 00:39:48.340
between the bone that faces
to the side in Acanthostega,

00:39:48.340 --> 00:39:50.150
and backwards in Eusthenopteron.

00:39:50.150 --> 00:39:51.860
And then you just add the other bones in.

00:39:51.860 --> 00:39:55.910
If you add the forearm
bones, the radius and ulna,

00:39:55.910 --> 00:39:58.260
turns out that the radius
and ulna in Tiktaalik,

00:39:58.260 --> 00:40:02.440
just like Acanthostega, are
capable of flexion like yay.

00:40:02.440 --> 00:40:04.810
And indeed the radius can rotate inwards,

00:40:04.810 --> 00:40:06.680
and work with a motion called pronation,

00:40:06.680 --> 00:40:08.930
like moving your thumb inwards.

00:40:08.930 --> 00:40:10.240
And when you add the other bones in,

00:40:10.240 --> 00:40:12.820
we can begin to see what
Tiktaalik was able to do.

00:40:12.820 --> 00:40:15.370
Tiktaalik is specialized
into a form of a push-up,

00:40:15.370 --> 00:40:18.960
with elbow bent and wrist extended,

00:40:18.960 --> 00:40:21.760
with a small set of
palmish bones it could,

00:40:21.760 --> 00:40:24.810
and remember the fin webbing
is sticking out here as well,

00:40:24.810 --> 00:40:26.930
you can support the body
in a form of a push-up

00:40:26.930 --> 00:40:30.960
with a palm-equivalent
flush against the ground.

00:40:30.960 --> 00:40:32.300
What was nice about these specimens too,

00:40:32.300 --> 00:40:33.610
and it's something we
haven't really published it,

00:40:33.610 --> 00:40:36.010
is the notion that we can begin to see

00:40:36.010 --> 00:40:39.370
how the fin webbing
changes during this change.

00:40:39.370 --> 00:40:41.550
So you're looking at the type specimen,

00:40:41.550 --> 00:40:43.870
one of the better specimens of Tiktaalik,

00:40:43.870 --> 00:40:45.920
from the top, and here you see the fin

00:40:45.920 --> 00:40:47.440
with its fin webbing.

00:40:47.440 --> 00:40:50.100
We have several these
specimens that are intact,

00:40:50.100 --> 00:40:51.830
which show the relationship

00:40:51.830 --> 00:40:54.010
between the limb bones I just showed you,

00:40:54.010 --> 00:40:55.510
and the fin webbing.

00:40:55.510 --> 00:40:56.970
And that's really important,

00:40:56.970 --> 00:41:00.500
because, if you look at a
fish like Eusthenopteron

00:41:00.500 --> 00:41:02.180
and Acanthostega, you see the big shift

00:41:02.180 --> 00:41:04.140
in the fin webbing, they lose it.

00:41:04.140 --> 00:41:05.570
fish have fin webbing,

00:41:05.570 --> 00:41:07.140
limbed animals do not.

00:41:07.140 --> 00:41:08.230
If you look at Tiktaalik,

00:41:08.230 --> 00:41:10.120
it's reduced the fin webbing,

00:41:10.120 --> 00:41:12.620
but it's done so in a very important way.

00:41:12.620 --> 00:41:15.600
It's done so, not from the outside in,

00:41:15.600 --> 00:41:16.440
but from the inside out.

00:41:16.440 --> 00:41:18.880
It's done it over the joints.

00:41:18.880 --> 00:41:21.800
So where it's lost the fin
webbing and these big rods,

00:41:21.800 --> 00:41:24.300
is over the elbow joint
and over the wrist joint.

00:41:24.300 --> 00:41:25.410
Which totally makes sense,

00:41:25.410 --> 00:41:28.923
those are the areas
where the fin would bend.

00:41:31.330 --> 00:41:33.790
So this is a sort of more
or less what we think

00:41:33.790 --> 00:41:35.860
what the fin of Tiktaalik was able to do,

00:41:35.860 --> 00:41:38.950
function like a paddle, or like a prop,

00:41:38.950 --> 00:41:42.220
enabling the creature to do a push up.

00:41:42.220 --> 00:41:45.580
This is the reconstruction of
Tiktaalik as it was in 2006,

00:41:45.580 --> 00:41:48.280
as a flathead with eyes
on top, pair of nostrils,

00:41:48.280 --> 00:41:51.210
has a neck where the head is
separate from the shoulder,

00:41:51.210 --> 00:41:54.060
and key in this, is
the loss of many bones,

00:41:54.060 --> 00:41:56.700
including the opercular bone which the,

00:41:56.700 --> 00:41:58.560
a whole series of opercular bones.

00:41:58.560 --> 00:42:00.820
It has a fin webbing and
inside that fin webbing

00:42:00.820 --> 00:42:04.370
is an upper arm bones,
forearm bones the equivalence,

00:42:04.370 --> 00:42:06.663
and both proximal carpal
and distal carpal bones

00:42:06.663 --> 00:42:10.110
that is the equivalence of
a wrist, big expanded ribs.

00:42:10.110 --> 00:42:11.640
We now know a lot about the hind fin,

00:42:11.640 --> 00:42:12.760
with the pelvis and so forth,

00:42:12.760 --> 00:42:14.310
we're lacking the femur

00:42:14.310 --> 00:42:16.480
so that's why I haven't drawn it in yet.

00:42:16.480 --> 00:42:17.510
One of the key things here

00:42:17.510 --> 00:42:19.141
is really understanding
Tiktaalik as a living animal,

00:42:19.141 --> 00:42:21.379
because then we can begin
to see this transformation,

00:42:21.379 --> 00:42:23.329
And that's what we are going to get to.

00:42:24.310 --> 00:42:25.220
One of things about Tiktaalik,

00:42:25.220 --> 00:42:28.100
is if it's supporting itself
as the appendanges suggest,

00:42:28.100 --> 00:42:30.090
on the ground like in a push-up,

00:42:30.090 --> 00:42:31.990
that's when the neck
becomes comes quite handy.

00:42:31.990 --> 00:42:35.700
If you look at a fish, it has
a head fused to the shoulder,

00:42:35.700 --> 00:42:37.220
and it does so by a series of bones

00:42:37.220 --> 00:42:39.030
at the back of the skull,

00:42:39.030 --> 00:42:42.210
and a series of opercular
bones, a whole opercular series

00:42:42.210 --> 00:42:45.000
that connect the cheek to the shoulder.

00:42:45.000 --> 00:42:46.500
These bones, I should
say the opercular bones,

00:42:46.500 --> 00:42:47.430
have several functions,

00:42:47.430 --> 00:42:50.130
they actually connect
the head to the shoulder.

00:42:50.130 --> 00:42:52.150
They function in
breathing in fish as well.

00:42:52.150 --> 00:42:55.530
They're pumps that draw
water across the gills.

00:42:55.530 --> 00:42:57.787
One of the big changes in
the transition to tetrapods,

00:42:57.787 --> 00:42:58.830
the limbed animals,

00:42:58.830 --> 00:43:00.400
is the loss of all these bones,

00:43:00.400 --> 00:43:01.750
so not only do you have a neck,

00:43:01.750 --> 00:43:03.930
but you've lost the operculum as well.

00:43:03.930 --> 00:43:05.500
And it turns out Tiktaalik
is much the same.

00:43:05.500 --> 00:43:07.700
It's evolved the ability to do push-ups,

00:43:07.700 --> 00:43:08.590
and at the same time

00:43:08.590 --> 00:43:10.580
it's lost this whole series of bones here.

00:43:10.580 --> 00:43:13.720
And what this shows is,
with this opercular series,

00:43:13.720 --> 00:43:16.770
is how one change, loss of simple bones,

00:43:16.770 --> 00:43:19.350
can affect several traits of the creature,

00:43:19.350 --> 00:43:22.321
from head mobility, which
is important for locomotion

00:43:22.321 --> 00:43:24.350
and the variety of behaviors it has,

00:43:24.350 --> 00:43:25.530
to breathing as well.

00:43:25.530 --> 00:43:27.370
Because as you lose the operculum,

00:43:27.370 --> 00:43:29.060
there are new ways that have to come about

00:43:29.060 --> 00:43:30.823
to bring water through the mouth.

00:43:33.130 --> 00:43:35.300
So what's Tiktaalik specialized to do?

