It's also an animal that's
able to live at the margin

00:43:45.445 --> 00:43:47.533
of water and land,

00:43:48.380 --> 00:43:50.090
and to feed as a carnivore,

00:43:50.090 --> 00:43:51.260
to feed either on fish

00:43:51.260 --> 00:43:53.251
or on the large variety of invertebrates

00:43:53.251 --> 00:43:55.080
that are present on land,

00:43:55.080 --> 00:43:57.173
and in the air at this time as well.

00:43:59.500 --> 00:44:03.470
So if you look at the
family tree and you plot

00:44:03.470 --> 00:44:05.270
with all the various
characters that we can do,

00:44:05.270 --> 00:44:07.310
Tiktaalik turns out to
be very closely related

00:44:07.310 --> 00:44:08.297
to limbed animals.

00:44:08.297 --> 00:44:11.508
And so no surprise given all
the features that we found.

00:44:11.508 --> 00:44:13.266
Now to really make sense of this,

00:44:13.266 --> 00:44:14.860
and to get back to the
whole point of the talk,

00:44:14.860 --> 00:44:17.230
which is really understanding
great transformations.

00:44:17.230 --> 00:44:18.190
Remember I opened with up the fact

00:44:18.190 --> 00:44:19.540
that this is an integrative discipline,

00:44:19.540 --> 00:44:20.970
this is something we have to pull in data

00:44:20.970 --> 00:44:23.100
from many different lines of inquiry.

00:44:23.100 --> 00:44:24.840
When it really comes down,
we have to think of ways

00:44:24.840 --> 00:44:27.237
to integrate these studies of fossils.

00:44:27.237 --> 00:44:29.030
And I should say right off the bat,

00:44:29.030 --> 00:44:32.550
that Tiktaalik only gains
meaning in relationship

00:44:32.550 --> 00:44:34.280
to the other fossils that
we have in this sequence

00:44:34.280 --> 00:44:35.360
in this series here okay.

00:44:35.360 --> 00:44:36.690
It alone doesn't tell us anything.

00:44:36.690 --> 00:44:38.411
It's this whole batch
of things which tell us

00:44:38.411 --> 00:44:40.043
how this transition happened.

00:44:41.620 --> 00:44:43.190
But we really have to begin to think about

00:44:43.190 --> 00:44:44.500
what living fish can tell us,

00:44:44.500 --> 00:44:47.610
and how they can, what lessons
can we learn from them about

00:44:47.610 --> 00:44:51.943
how fish evolved to walk on
land and to live on land.

00:44:51.943 --> 00:44:52.776
And there's a couple things,

00:44:52.776 --> 00:44:54.330
I'm just gonna to isolate three.

00:44:54.330 --> 00:44:56.960
One is, we can study
their genes and genetics.

00:44:56.960 --> 00:44:58.720
That is, we can look at the genetic recipe

00:44:58.720 --> 00:45:00.600
that builds the bodies of fish,

00:45:00.600 --> 00:45:02.227
and builds the bodies
of land living animals

00:45:02.227 --> 00:45:04.620
and we can ask the question
what's different among them,

00:45:04.620 --> 00:45:06.410
and we can do that at the level of organs,

00:45:06.410 --> 00:45:08.000
we can do that the level of tissues,

00:45:08.000 --> 00:45:09.710
we can do that at a variety
of different levels,

00:45:09.710 --> 00:45:12.143
with increasing precision every year.

00:45:13.130 --> 00:45:14.620
We can look at appendage support,

00:45:14.620 --> 00:45:16.690
how do fish support themselves
with their appendage,

00:45:16.690 --> 00:45:18.740
what are the models of living organisms

00:45:18.740 --> 00:45:21.060
that do this kind of thing today,

00:45:21.060 --> 00:45:22.270
and we can look at air breathing.

00:45:22.270 --> 00:45:23.900
How does air breathing happen in fish?

00:45:23.900 --> 00:45:25.700
And you know we can do
with, this is arbitrary,

00:45:25.700 --> 00:45:27.596
I could add in another four
or five things on here,

00:45:27.596 --> 00:45:29.810
but I wanted to give you
some take-home messages

00:45:29.810 --> 00:45:32.360
about what we can learn from living fish.

00:45:32.360 --> 00:45:33.740
Well if you look at it,

00:45:33.740 --> 00:45:35.200
what I'm going to show you here is,

00:45:35.200 --> 00:45:36.430
what you can see are limbs,

00:45:36.430 --> 00:45:38.690
these are fins up here
and limbs down here.

00:45:38.690 --> 00:45:41.640
If you take living creatures
alone, with no fossils,

00:45:41.640 --> 00:45:43.227
we have limbs with one bone, two bones,

00:45:43.227 --> 00:45:45.090
little bones and fingers,

00:45:45.090 --> 00:45:46.830
and I'm showing you a chicken and a human,

00:45:46.830 --> 00:45:48.070
and they have a one bone, two bone,

00:45:48.070 --> 00:45:49.320
sort of finger arrangement as well,

00:45:49.320 --> 00:45:51.800
despite the fact that it's in a fin,

00:45:51.800 --> 00:45:53.900
and if you're compare to fish
fins that are alive today

00:45:53.900 --> 00:45:56.020
they don't look a whole lot alike.

00:45:56.020 --> 00:45:57.300
Here's a lungfish here,

00:45:57.300 --> 00:46:01.180
a creature Neoceratodus from Australia,

