00:46:04.700 --> 00:46:05.930
that look very limb-like,

00:46:05.930 --> 00:46:07.950
neither do any of these other fins here.

00:46:07.950 --> 00:46:09.280
Where the comparison gains meaning

00:46:09.280 --> 00:46:12.160
are when we add the fossils
to this evolutionary tree,

00:46:12.160 --> 00:46:16.080
that we begin to see this one
bone two bone limb pattern

00:46:16.080 --> 00:46:18.710
appearing and evolving in our own lineage.

00:46:18.710 --> 00:46:20.490
So if you just take living creatures,

00:46:20.490 --> 00:46:22.060
this transition from fin,

00:46:22.060 --> 00:46:24.930
I'm sorry from fin to limb, looks vast.

00:46:24.930 --> 00:46:27.010
But when we start to
add in the fossil taxa,

00:46:27.010 --> 00:46:28.650
the fossil creatures and species,

00:46:28.650 --> 00:46:31.220
you begin to see the links between them.

00:46:31.220 --> 00:46:32.560
but really where it's important

00:46:32.560 --> 00:46:35.280
is we can study the genetics
and developmental biology

00:46:35.280 --> 00:46:36.410
of living creatures,

00:46:36.410 --> 00:46:37.641
in a way that we can't do

00:46:37.641 --> 00:46:41.550
with the ones that have been
dead for 375 million years.

00:46:41.550 --> 00:46:43.750
And when we do that, what
we can begin to understand

00:46:43.750 --> 00:46:45.960
is the genetic toolkit and the recipe

00:46:45.960 --> 00:46:48.750
that builds the skeleton of an appendage.

00:46:48.750 --> 00:46:50.040
We can begin to ask the question is,

00:46:50.040 --> 00:46:51.648
what are the set of genetic interactions

00:46:51.648 --> 00:46:54.330
that build the pattern
of one bone two bones,

00:46:54.330 --> 00:46:55.920
little bones, fingers?

00:46:55.920 --> 00:46:58.549
We begin to ask the question,
what's the genetic recipe

00:46:58.549 --> 00:47:00.330
that controls the number of bones

00:47:00.330 --> 00:47:01.560
in different parts of the body?

00:47:01.560 --> 00:47:03.680
It's size and shape and so forth.

00:47:03.680 --> 00:47:05.470
And if we do that we can begin to see,

00:47:05.470 --> 00:47:08.120
and by about the late 90s we began to see

00:47:08.120 --> 00:47:10.320
that there's a very
characteristic set of patterns

00:47:10.320 --> 00:47:12.490
of gene activity and gene function,

00:47:12.490 --> 00:47:14.000
genes called the Hox genes and others,

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:15.980
I'm not going to go through them all,

00:47:15.980 --> 00:47:18.210
that characterized the
development of limbs.

00:47:18.210 --> 00:47:19.600
It's a cascade of events,

00:47:19.600 --> 00:47:21.840
of cellular events and genetic events,

00:47:21.840 --> 00:47:23.370
that produced the pattern of limbs,

00:47:23.370 --> 00:47:25.910
I'm going to talk about
that more tomorrow.

00:47:25.910 --> 00:47:27.190
However what was really interesting

00:47:27.190 --> 00:47:28.640
is we knew what this stuff was,

00:47:28.640 --> 00:47:31.970
how it was happening in
chickens and mice and frogs.

00:47:31.970 --> 00:47:33.210
The real surprise came

00:47:33.210 --> 00:47:35.740
when we started to look at
these genetic interactions

00:47:35.740 --> 00:47:37.980
and processes acting in fish fins,

00:47:37.980 --> 00:47:39.490
and what was truly remarkable,

00:47:39.490 --> 00:47:41.670
is that many of the genetic processes

00:47:41.670 --> 00:47:44.470
that build the fins and the
skeleton of the fins of fish,

00:47:44.470 --> 00:47:46.770
and indeed that pattern
them, are very similar

00:47:46.770 --> 00:47:51.740
to those that pattern the
limbs of limbed animals.

00:47:51.740 --> 00:47:53.780
And in fact it's very clear that you know,

00:47:53.780 --> 00:47:55.450
if you were to ask the question,

00:47:55.450 --> 00:47:56.840
are there any new genes

00:47:56.840 --> 00:47:59.510
that are patterning the
limbs of limbed animals

00:47:59.510 --> 00:48:01.110
that aren't in present in fins.

00:48:01.110 --> 00:48:02.770
The answer's likely no.

00:48:02.770 --> 00:48:05.070
That is it's not like the
origin of limbs involved,

00:48:05.070 --> 00:48:07.860
necessarily involved the origin
of whole new sets of genes,

00:48:07.860 --> 00:48:11.210
it involved whole new sets
of genetic interactions,

00:48:11.210 --> 00:48:13.370
and new ways of genes
being turned on and off

00:48:13.370 --> 00:48:14.850
in new places and so forth.

00:48:14.850 --> 00:48:17.030
so it's using existing genes in new ways,

00:48:17.030 --> 00:48:18.180
and reconfiguring them.

00:48:19.590 --> 00:48:22.150
So the genetic, if you want toolkit,

00:48:22.150 --> 00:48:24.430
that's necessary to build appendages,

00:48:24.430 --> 00:48:25.370
was already present

00:48:25.370 --> 00:48:27.740
when a lot of these fossils hit the scene.

00:48:27.740 --> 00:48:29.963
So the repertoire was already there.

00:48:30.850 --> 00:48:33.530
If we look at appendage
support in extant creatures,

00:48:33.530 --> 00:48:35.090
what you'll find is a lot of fish

00:48:35.090 --> 00:48:37.460
actually support themselves
with their appendages.

00:48:37.460 --> 00:48:40.230
Most famous among this is the mudskipper.

00:48:40.230 --> 00:48:42.610
Mudskippers can live on
land for a period of time,

00:48:42.610 --> 00:48:45.150
about 24 hours about the max in the mud,

00:48:45.150 --> 00:48:47.993
and they have appendages but
the little type of elbow.

00:48:49.020 --> 00:48:50.110
And if you look at frog fish,

00:48:50.110 --> 00:48:53.930
the frog fish is a creature
that can walk in the water,

00:48:53.930 --> 00:48:55.940
this is actually an aquatic
creature they can walk around.

00:48:55.940 --> 00:48:59.560
It even has a little sort of
elbow and a distal paddle.

00:48:59.560 --> 00:49:01.180
What's remarkable about
all these creatures

00:49:01.180 --> 00:49:02.950
that have evolved to sort of walk

00:49:02.950 --> 00:49:05.240
or support themselves
with their appendages,

00:49:05.240 --> 00:49:08.360
is oftentimes they do it with
equivalent kinds of joints.

00:49:08.360 --> 00:49:11.270
shoulders and and paddles and so forth.

00:49:11.270 --> 00:49:12.780
But in each case that they do it,

00:49:12.780 --> 00:49:14.650
they do it with different bones.

00:49:14.650 --> 00:49:16.960
So here is the frogfish fin,

00:49:16.960 --> 00:49:19.320
and you remember we have this
one bone two bone little bone

00:49:19.320 --> 00:49:21.320
ray pattern, this is nothing like that.

00:49:21.320 --> 00:49:24.340
This is three bones, a big
old plate, a big old rod,

00:49:24.340 --> 00:49:27.310
a big old rod here and a
bunch of spikes coming off.

00:49:27.310 --> 00:49:29.770
That's very different
from the limb pattern

00:49:29.770 --> 00:49:31.700
in early, in limbed animals.

00:49:31.700 --> 00:49:33.500
So what you see is when fish,

00:49:33.500 --> 00:49:36.850
that are distantly related to
Tiktaalik and other creatures

00:49:36.850 --> 00:49:38.460
evolved appendage support,

00:49:38.460 --> 00:49:40.310
they evolved similar kinds of joints

00:49:40.310 --> 00:49:42.610
but they do it with
different sets of bones.

00:49:42.610 --> 00:49:44.371
Only one lineage did it our way,

00:49:44.371 --> 00:49:48.330
and that's the Tiktaalik
lobe-finned fish of ourlineage.

00:49:48.330 --> 00:49:49.810
Finally you can ask the question you know,

00:49:49.810 --> 00:49:51.650
the creatures that are
doing appendage support

00:49:51.650 --> 00:49:54.230
and walking in mud and so
forth, how they breathe?

00:49:54.230 --> 00:49:57.120
Well if you look at the
evolutionary tree of fish,

00:49:57.120 --> 00:49:58.570
and you ask the question,

00:49:58.570 --> 00:49:59.980
how many of these things
are air breathers?

00:49:59.980 --> 00:50:02.350
There are about 30,000
different species of fish,

00:50:02.350 --> 00:50:04.610
say 29,000 of them or so.

00:50:04.610 --> 00:50:06.520
Of those that are looked at so far,

00:50:06.520 --> 00:50:08.442
in the last major monograph
somebody identified

00:50:08.442 --> 00:50:11.200
375 species of air breathing fish,

00:50:11.200 --> 00:50:12.100
which is what's been looked at,

00:50:12.100 --> 00:50:13.690
there are certainly a whole lot more,

00:50:13.690 --> 00:50:16.660
in 49 different families
and if you map it to a tree,

00:50:16.660 --> 00:50:18.500
it evolved at least 24 times.

00:50:18.500 --> 00:50:21.030
That likely is about three times to love,

00:50:21.030 --> 00:50:23.180
based on if you look at
the trees that mapped on.

00:50:23.180 --> 00:50:25.150
So air breathing in fish has evolved

00:50:25.150 --> 00:50:29.070
many times independently
in living extant fish.

00:50:29.070 --> 00:50:30.600
And how do they do it?

00:50:30.600 --> 00:50:33.870
The most common way that fish breathe air,

00:50:33.870 --> 00:50:36.240
at least in the evolutionary tree,

00:50:36.240 --> 00:50:37.540
is they use lungs.

00:50:37.540 --> 00:50:38.900
In fact lungs are primitive,

00:50:38.900 --> 00:50:41.150
lungs are primitive to this
thing here, a Polypterus,

00:50:41.150 --> 00:50:42.180
to lung fish,

00:50:42.180 --> 00:50:43.400
indeed if you look at Tiktaalik

00:50:43.400 --> 00:50:44.920
and where it fits on this tree,

00:50:44.920 --> 00:50:46.780
Tiktaalik's right about here.

00:50:46.780 --> 00:50:49.890
So lungs hit the scene
well before Tiktaalik,

00:50:49.890 --> 00:50:51.850
and even its distant relatives

00:50:51.850 --> 00:50:54.230
were around in Devonian streams.

00:50:54.230 --> 00:50:56.979
They evolved in each case
like in the lung fish

00:50:56.979 --> 00:50:59.300
they evolved to allow creatures to breathe

00:50:59.300 --> 00:51:01.630
when water gets anoxic and oxygen poor,

00:51:01.630 --> 00:51:04.100
they go up and gulp air
in many different ways.

00:51:04.100 --> 00:51:05.580
And there other examples as well,

00:51:05.580 --> 00:51:07.520
there are diverse air breathing
organs in this group here

00:51:07.520 --> 00:51:08.870
which is very specious.

00:51:08.870 --> 00:51:11.690
Some of these creatures
vascularize their swim bladders,

00:51:11.690 --> 00:51:13.320
they vascularize their mouths

00:51:13.320 --> 00:51:16.040
there are numerous strategies
for air breathing in fish,

00:51:16.040 --> 00:51:18.480
but lungs are the ones
that are actually primitive

00:51:18.480 --> 00:51:19.430
to our own lineage.

00:51:20.560 --> 00:51:23.133
So returning to the
initial sort of challenge.

00:51:25.210 --> 00:51:27.794
With air breathing evolving
multiple times independently

00:51:27.794 --> 00:51:31.330
in fish, with the genes
necessary to build limbs,

00:51:31.330 --> 00:51:33.190
already present in fish fins,

00:51:33.190 --> 00:51:34.750
with appendage support appearing

00:51:34.750 --> 00:51:36.820
in numerous kinds of fish independently,

00:51:36.820 --> 00:51:38.730
with intermediates in the fossil record

00:51:38.730 --> 00:51:40.625
at just the right time
in the fossil record,

00:51:40.625 --> 00:51:43.540
you, you know don't ask the question,

00:51:43.540 --> 00:51:45.860
how could this transition
ever have happened.

00:51:45.860 --> 00:51:48.590
Ask the question, why
did it happen only once.

00:51:48.590 --> 00:51:51.128
It's so, this barrier
between water and land

00:51:51.128 --> 00:51:53.560
seems to be very porous,

00:51:53.560 --> 00:51:55.770
at least for creatures
that are specializing

00:51:55.770 --> 00:51:58.480
for the interface between water and land.

00:51:58.480 --> 00:51:59.740
And why did it evolve only once,

00:51:59.740 --> 00:52:00.700
I can only speculate.

00:52:00.700 --> 00:52:02.700
In our lineage and only evolved once.

00:52:02.700 --> 00:52:04.890
Perhaps it's some sort of
ecological king of the hill

00:52:04.890 --> 00:52:07.600
situation where, you have an incumbent,

00:52:07.600 --> 00:52:10.890
and it sort of displaces
any other lineages

00:52:10.890 --> 00:52:12.230
that would evolve to walk on land,

00:52:12.230 --> 00:52:15.080
'cause there's already an
incumbent set of species there.

00:52:16.920 --> 00:52:18.900
So all this is in terms
of its extrapolating

00:52:18.900 --> 00:52:20.470
to great transformations.

00:52:20.470 --> 00:52:23.347
You know one way of thinking
about great transformations,

00:52:23.347 --> 00:52:25.890
is the popular one you
see day-to-day in cartoons

00:52:25.890 --> 00:52:27.650
and oftentimes in texts,

00:52:27.650 --> 00:52:30.090
which is as a ladder-like
notion of change that is,

00:52:30.090 --> 00:52:32.087
you know one species
leads to another species

00:52:32.087 --> 00:52:34.100
leads to another species.

00:52:34.100 --> 00:52:35.480
That's not how it works.

00:52:35.480 --> 00:52:37.800
that's not how the water
to land transition works,

00:52:37.800 --> 00:52:39.960
that's not how any of the
other great transitions works.

00:52:39.960 --> 00:52:42.770
It's not like Tiktaalik and its kin

00:52:42.770 --> 00:52:43.990
were sitting around thinking,

00:52:43.990 --> 00:52:47.000
oh golly I wanna to evolve
lungs so I can walk on land,

00:52:47.000 --> 00:52:49.170
I wanna evolve wrists to walk on land.

00:52:49.170 --> 00:52:51.240
It was adaptation to life in water,

00:52:51.240 --> 00:52:53.460
it was diversification in life in water,

00:52:53.460 --> 00:52:55.620
finding new strategies to
live on the water bottom

00:52:55.620 --> 00:52:56.453
in the shallows,

00:52:56.453 --> 00:52:58.330
in the interface between water and land,

00:52:58.330 --> 00:53:00.210
on the mud flats and so forth,

00:53:00.210 --> 00:53:03.200
that led to the diverse
adaptations which became useful

00:53:03.200 --> 00:53:05.630
when the need came to walk on land.

00:53:05.630 --> 00:53:08.180
And so what we think about is
evolution not as this ladder,

00:53:08.180 --> 00:53:11.410
but as Darwin originally
proposed, as a tree.

00:53:11.410 --> 00:53:12.750
As a tree of evolution

00:53:12.750 --> 00:53:15.043
with a diverse set of strategies evolving.

00:53:16.350 --> 00:53:18.410
And I should say that
there is a unifying theme

00:53:18.410 --> 00:53:19.830
to many of the great transformations,

00:53:19.830 --> 00:53:21.930
I'm gonna just close
with a series of these.

00:53:21.930 --> 00:53:24.047
You can think of the
transformation from something like

00:53:24.047 --> 00:53:26.240
